    "constituents_description": "The most important healing constituents of Senna benitoensis are anthraquinone glycosides sennoside A, sennoside B, sennoside C, and sennoside D, which are responsible for its purgative properties, and anthraquinone aglycon emodin, which contributes to its laxative and anti-inflammatory effects. Sennosides A, B, C, and D are anthraquinone glycosides that are hydrolyzed to emodin in the body, emodin has been shown to have anti-inflammatory and laxative effects. The anthraquinone glycosides are not absorbed in the digestive tract, but are instead hydrolyzed by intestinal bacteria to release the active anthraquinone aglycons, including emodin. Emodin has been reported to have anti-inflammatory and immunomodulatory effects, and is responsible for the laxative effects of Senna benitoensis. The laxative and anti-inflammatory properties of Senna benitoensis make it a useful treatment for constipation and certain gastrointestinal disorders.",
