    "preparations_description": "The main herbal preparations of Senna benitoensis are derived from its leaves and pods, which contain anthraquinone glycosides. Senna tea, a popular preparation, is made by infusing the leaves and pods in hot water to release these compounds, which act as a laxative. Senna tincture is a concentrated liquid extract of Senna benitoensis, often used in homeopathic medicine to stimulate bowel movements. Senna infusion is similar to tea but often uses a higher ratio of plant material to water, resulting in a stronger laxative effect. Senna capsules and extract are also available, typically standardized to contain a specific amount of anthraquinones, providing a convenient and controlled dosage of the herb's active compounds.",
